    </div>
    <div class="asset-content entry-content">

        <div class="asset-body">
            <div class="kw-format"><p><a href="http://blogs.answersingenesis.org/blogs/ken-ham/2013/10/19/who-is-dan-phelps/" rel="external ">Dan Phelps</a>, president of the <a href="http://www.uky.edu/OtherOrgs/KPS/welcome.html" rel="external ">Kentucky Paleontological Society</a>, will participate in an “extended interview” with <a href="http://www.answersingenesis.org/outreach/speakers/terry-mortenson/bio/" rel="external ">Terry Mortenson</a> of Answers in Genesis. The participants will discuss the question, “<a href="http://weku.fm/post/eastern-standard-teaching-creationism-harmful-children-society" rel="external ">Is teaching creationism harmful to children, society?</a>” at 11:00 a.m., Eastern Standard Time, Thursday, January 30, on WEKU of Richmond, Kentucky. It looks like you can get it <a href="http://weku.fm/schedule" rel="external ">streaming</a>. I will refrain from noting that modern journalism thinks there are two sides to every question, even when there are not.</p>

<p>Does any reader know of any other, similar warm-ups or “extended interviews”?</p>

