<h4>
<img SRC="rd_ball.gif" ALT align="BOTTOM">&nbsp;<a NAME="chaos"></a>Chaos
theory</h4>

<dt>
Chaos theory is connected to evolutionary theory in a quantitative way.
It appears that evolutionary systems are mostly systems that are far from
equilibrium, and that the dynamics of such systems, or clusters of systems
cannot be described by linear-dynamics. Therefore there are a lot of connections
between chaos-theory and evolutionary theory.</dt>

<h1>
<img SRC="http://www-chaos.umd.edu/images/chaoslogo.gif" align="CENTER"></h1>

<dd>
Chaos in Maryland: <a href="http://www-chaos.umd.edu" target="new">maryland chaos</a>,
where the picture is from featuring lots of pictures and some theory.</dd>

<dd>
The Society for Nonlinear Dynamics and Econometrics (SNDE) <a href="http://www.iia.org/~mizracb/snde.html" target="new">homepage</a>.</dd>

<dd>
A hypertext <a href="http://www.fmb.mmu.ac.uk:80/~bruce/combib/" target="new">Bibliography
of Measures of Complexity</a> at Manchester Metropolitan University.</dd>

<dd>
Los Alamos National Labs <a href="http://cnls-www.lanl.gov/" target="new">CNLS Welcome</a></dd>

<dd>
The <a href="http://www.prairienet.org/business/ptech/chaos.html" target="new">chaos
Network at prairienet</a></dd>

<dd>
<a href="http://www.cc.duth.gr/~mboudour/nonlin.html" target="new">Nonlinearity and
Complexity home page</a> at DUTh (Democritus University of Thrace in Xanthi,
Greece)</dd>

<dd>
<a href="http://www.uvm.edu/~fabraham/chaopsyk.html" target="new">ChaoPsyk Browser</a></dd>

<dd>
<a href="gopher://gopher.tmn.com" target="new">gopher://gopher.tmn.com</a></dd>

<h4>
<img SRC="rd_ball.gif" ALT align="BOTTOM">
<a href="http://www.hanscees.com/mem.htm">Memetics</a></h4>
Memetics is the study that sees cultural 'rules' [memes] as the analog
to genes. It focusses on replicative cultural artifacts [ideas, behavioral
rules, solution spaces for problems] that are transmitted. In contrary
to classic views the human is seen as an evolutionary being. This means
that a human must learn, its actions are biased by its past and its thoughts
and that its knowledge is limited. It uses memes to think, act and learn.
These memes can be innovations, but generally they are imitated from others.
In this sence there is place for the focus of what memes do to people,
that is how they can guide human thought and action. As with genes my suspicion
is that memes influence each others chances of being replicated, and exist
in complex systems in human brains, books, etc. For many people the concept
may seem threatening, because it may seem to suggest that people are not
free even in their mind. Because memes can only be picked up if encountered,
and memes already in the brain select partly the new memes that are included.
If true this is an example how the idea of freedom is connected in some
way to the idea of memes, and how it restricts the acceptance of that idea.&nbsp;

<p><br><img SRC="http://cutl.city.unisa.edu.au/louvre/about/BSD-daemon.gif" ALT HSPACE="3" height="64" width="64" align="LEFT">
<hr>
   </div>


</body>
